<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>GNU on KevCaz's Website</title><link>https://kevcaz.github.io/tags/gnu/</link><description>Recent content in GNU on KevCaz's Website</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en-us</language><copyright>Content under CC0 1.0 Universal unless otherwise specified.</copyright><lastBuildDate>Tue, 15 Jan 2019 00:00:00 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://kevcaz.github.io/tags/gnu/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Merge .csv files into a single .xlsx file with ssconvert</title><link>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2019/01/2019-01-15_merge_csv_files/</link><pubDate>Tue, 15 Jan 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2019/01/2019-01-15_merge_csv_files/</guid><description>&lt;p>In a previous note, I explained &lt;a href="../../notes/gnu/xlsx2csv/">how to convert &lt;code>.xlsx&lt;/code> into &lt;code>.csv&lt;/code> with ssconvert&lt;/a>. Today, I wanted to do the reverse operation, so I looked up on the Internet and found &lt;a href="https://ubuntuforums.org/showthread.php?t=2263957">this answer on ubuntu forums&lt;/a>: assuming you need to merge &lt;code>file1.csv&lt;/code> and &lt;code>file2.csv&lt;/code> into &lt;code>all.xlsx&lt;/code> (in two separate sheets) then all you have to do is:&lt;/p>
&lt;pre tabindex="0">&lt;code>ssconvert --merge-to=all.xlsx file1.csv file2.csv
&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;p>The short option for &lt;code>--merge-to=&lt;/code> is &lt;code>-M&lt;/code> (see &lt;code>man ssconvert&lt;/code>), so what I did was:&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>More radio stations</title><link>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2018/11/2018-11-04_more_radio_stations/</link><pubDate>Sun, 04 Nov 2018 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2018/11/2018-11-04_more_radio_stations/</guid><description>&lt;p>I am a radio listener and a podcast addict &amp;#x1f4fb;! Yesterday, I spent some time adding more
radio stations with &lt;a href="https://wiki.gnome.org/Apps/Rhythmbox">Rhythmbox&lt;/a>. I
really love this software, it is simple and do everything I need, adding a new
radio station with it was straightforward but it requires first to find the
URLs of the radio stations to be added as there is no radio browser integrated
(but have a look at &lt;a href="https://github.com/fossfreedom/radio-browser">radio-browser&lt;/a>).
So to be more accurate, I spent some time finding where to find such URLs!&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Modify and combine a set of files in one</title><link>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2018/10/2018-10-29_modify_and_combine/</link><pubDate>Mon, 29 Oct 2018 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2018/10/2018-10-29_modify_and_combine/</guid><description>&lt;p>Today I was looking for a way to combine a set of files in one but before
appending a given file, the 2 first lines as well as the last line had to be removed. On Stackoverflow &lt;i class="fa fa-stack-overflow" aria-hidden="true">&lt;/i> I found a couple of answers (see questions &lt;a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/18006581/how-to-append-contents-of-multiple-files-into-one-file">18006581&lt;/a>, &lt;a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/12176492/shell-delete-the-last-line-of-a-huge-text-log-file">12176492&lt;/a> and &lt;a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/5410757/delete-lines-in-a-text-file-that-contain-a-specific-string">5410757&lt;/a>) and based on these I decided to use a combination of
&lt;a href="https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/html_node/head-invocation.html">head&lt;/a> and &lt;a href="https://www.gnu.org/software/coreutils/manual/html_node/tail-invocation.html">tail&lt;/a>. I ended up creating the following shell script:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">
&lt;table style="border-spacing:0;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;">&lt;tr>&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">1
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">2
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">3
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">4
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">5
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">6
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">7
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;;width:100%">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code class="language-sh" data-lang="sh">&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>&lt;span style="color:#9893a5">#!/bin/bash
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>&lt;span style="color:#9893a5">&lt;/span>touch biblio.yaml
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>&lt;span style="color:#286983">for&lt;/span> f in refs/*.yml
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>&lt;span style="color:#286983">do&lt;/span>
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span> tail -n+3 &lt;span style="color:#d7827e">$f&lt;/span> &lt;span style="color:#797593">|&lt;/span> head -n-1 &amp;gt;&amp;gt; biblio.yaml
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span> &lt;span style="color:#d7827e">echo&lt;/span> &lt;span style="color:#ea9d34">&amp;#34;\n&amp;#34;&lt;/span> &amp;gt;&amp;gt; biblio.yaml
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>&lt;span style="color:#286983">done&lt;/span>
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;p>Let&amp;rsquo;s break it down:&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>.xlsx to .csv with ssconvert</title><link>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2018/10/2018-10-18_xlsx_to_csv/</link><pubDate>Thu, 18 Oct 2018 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2018/10/2018-10-18_xlsx_to_csv/</guid><description>&lt;p>Even if I use &lt;a href="https://www.libreoffice.org/discover/calc/">Calc&lt;/a> more
often than &lt;a href="http://www.gnumeric.org/">Gnumeric&lt;/a> (and actually I tried to
spend as less time as possible on spreadsheet programs), the latter
provides a tool I&amp;rsquo;m fond of,
&lt;a href="http://manpages.ubuntu.com/manpages/bionic/man1/ssconvert.1.html">ssconvert&lt;/a>:&lt;/p>
&lt;blockquote>
&lt;p>ssconvert - a command line spreadsheet format converter&lt;/p>&lt;/blockquote>
&lt;p>It offers a very efficient way to convert &lt;code>.xlsx&lt;/code> into &lt;code>.csv&lt;/code>,
for instance:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;div style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">
&lt;table style="border-spacing:0;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;">&lt;tr>&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">1
&lt;/span>&lt;span style="white-space:pre;-webkit-user-select:none;user-select:none;margin-right:0.4em;padding:0 0.4em 0 0.4em;color:#7f7f7f">2
&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>
&lt;td style="vertical-align:top;padding:0;margin:0;border:0;;width:100%">
&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#575279;background-color:#faf4ed;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code class="language-sh" data-lang="sh">&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>mkdir csvFiles
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>ssconvert -S spreadsheet.xlsx csvFiles/%s.csv
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/td>&lt;/tr>&lt;/table>
&lt;/div>
&lt;/div>&lt;p>I the command lines above, I first create the folder &amp;lsquo;csvFiles&amp;rsquo; with &lt;code>mkdir&lt;/code> and then I use
&lt;code>ssconvert&lt;/code> with option &lt;code>-S&lt;/code> that stands for &lt;code>--export-file-per-sheet&lt;/code>:&lt;/p></description></item></channel></rss>